We have carried out ﬁrst-principle calculations to investigate
the oxygen diﬀusion in double perovskite PrBaCo
which were experimentally reported, were found with one

metallic, and the state of the Fermi level exhibits the mixed
oxygen 2p and cobalt 3d characterization. Surprisingly, cobalt
ions in both octahedral and pyramidal sites possess an
intermediate spin state in the paramagnetic phase, diﬀering
from the typical interpretation of the metal
examined on the basis of the obtained magnetic and vacant
structures. The paramagnetic orthorhombic phase was taken
into account for the diﬀusion calculations, since it is
responsible for the situation in the temperature range of
interest for intermediate temperature solid-oxide fuel cell
applications. We conclude that the main contribution of
oxygen diﬀusivity is attributed to the migration from the Pr
O layer or vice versa along the direction
perpendicular to the one-dimensional oxygen-vacancy channel.
